<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="539" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="58.[79,1035,726,1325]" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">
<emphasis box="[120,253,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Description.</emphasis>
Cell ovoid or droplet-shaped, about 4±9 Mm long, 2.5±5 Mm wide, somewhat ¯exible and not ¯attened, with two ¯agella similar in length emerging subapically (about one-third of the way down). The ¯agella are slightly longer than the cell and not acronematic. The anterior ¯agellum projects in front of the body and beats with an asymmetric pattern, and the posterior ¯agellum trails behind the body and may be held in a curve or obliquely. Sometimes, the posterior ¯agellum beats sti‚y and rapidly in non-swimming cells. Cells usually swim by slow rotating movements and the cell bodies wag. When cells swim rapidly, the anterior ¯agellum beats quickly and cells do not wag. Cells may attach to the substratum by the tip of the trailing ¯agellum. In attached cells, cells may wag or tremble rapidly. Commonly observed in enrichment cultures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[79,1035,726,1325]" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">
<emphasis box="[120,226,1077,1101]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has been found in marine sites in subtropical 
<collectingCountry box="[929,1034,1077,1101]" name="Australia" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Australia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[133,227,1109,1133]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">England</collectingCountry>
, cell length range is reported to be 5±8.5 Mm (
<bibRefCitation author="TONG, S. M." box="[786,928,1109,1134]" pageId="58" pageNumber="539" pagination="536" refId="ref43745" refString="TONG, S. M., 1997 a, Heterotrophic ¯ agellates from the water column in Shark Bay, Western Australia, Marine Biology, 128, 517 ± 536." type="journal article" year="1997">
Tong, 1997 
<bibRefCitation author="SIMPSON, A. G. B. &amp; HOFF, J. &amp; BERNARD, C. &amp; BURTON, H. R. &amp; PATTERSON, D. J." box="[916,928,1109,1133]" pageId="58" pageNumber="539" pagination="225" refId="ref42978" refString="SIMPSON, A. G. B., HOFF, J., BERNARD, C., BURTON, H. R. and PATTERSON, D. J., 1997 b, The ultrastructure and systematic position of the euglenozoan Postgaardi mariagerensis Fenchel et al., Archiv fuEr Protistenkunde, 147, 213 ± 225." type="journal article" year="1997">a</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
, 1997b). Like naked bicosoecids (
<taxonomicName box="[377,481,1141,1165]" class="Bigyra" family="Cafeteriaceae" genus="Cafeteria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Bicosoecida" pageId="58" pageNumber="539" phylum="Bigyra" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[377,481,1141,1165]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Cafeteria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[552,682,1141,1165]" class="Bikosea" family="Cafeteriaceae" genus="Pseudobodo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Bicosoecales" pageId="58" pageNumber="539" phylum="Bigyra" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[552,682,1141,1165]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Pseudobodo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) this species attaches to the substratum by the tip of the posterior ¯agellum. This species can be distinguished from all species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[426,530,1205,1229]" class="Bigyra" family="Cafeteriaceae" genus="Cafeteria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Bicosoecida" pageId="58" pageNumber="539" phylum="Bigyra" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[426,530,1205,1229]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Cafeteria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the orientation and beat pattern of the ¯agella. It is similar to 
<emphasis box="[369,499,1237,1261]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Phyllomitus</emphasis>
in general shape, but is easily distinguished because the two ¯agella of 
<emphasis box="[396,526,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Phyllomitus</emphasis>
insert together to an anterior pocket, while those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S.M.Tong" authorityYear="1997" box="[180,338,1300,1324]" class="Bicoecea" family="Placidiaceae" genus="Pendulomonas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Placidiida" pageId="58" pageNumber="539" phylum="Bigyra" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[180,338,1300,1324]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="539">Pendulomonas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
insert separately in a subapical groove.
</paragraph>
